                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War, 1939/37: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Italy</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Phillips</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-09-01T20:00:00+01:00"
                            >September 1, 1939—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received September 1—4:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>361. My No. 355, September 1, 11 a.m. The French Ambassador saw Ciano this
                    morning at 11:30 and gave a favorable reply on behalf <pb facs="0419" n="407"
                        xml:id="pg_407"/> of his Government to the proposal to call a conference of
                    various European powers including Poland to consider the causes of existing
                    European friction. The French Embassy is not hopeful that any result will be
                    achieved through this action but considers that even the slightest opportunity
                    to avert a complete catastrophe should not be missed. The Embassy staff is
                    apparently ready to leave Italy at a moment’s notice should Italy be finally
                    drawn into the [war?].</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
